<subsection xml:id="subsec-Square-roots-of-decimals">
    <title>Square roots of decimals</title>
    <activity>
            <p>
                <alert>Work in groups</alert>
            </p>
            <p>
                1. Draw the following grids as shown below.
            </p>
                <sidebyside widths="25% 25% 25%">
            <image>
                <shortdescription></shortdescription>
                <latex-image>
                    \begin{tikzpicture}
                        \foreach \x in {0,1,2,3} {
                            \draw[thick,blue] (\x,0) -- (\x,3);
                        }
                        \foreach \y in {0,1,2,3} {
                            \draw[thick,blue] (0,\y) -- (3,\y);
                        }
                    \end{tikzpicture}
                </latex-image>
            </image>
            <image>
                <shortdescription></shortdescription>
                <latex-image>
                    \begin{tikzpicture}
                        \foreach \x in {0,1,2,3,4} {
                            \draw[thick,blue] (\x,0) -- (\x,4);
                        }
                        \foreach \y in {0,1,2,3,4} {
                            \draw[thick,blue] (0,\y) -- (4,\y);
                        }
                    \end{tikzpicture}
                </latex-image>
            </image>
            <image>
                <shortdescription></shortdescription>
                <latex-image>
                    \begin{tikzpicture}
                        \foreach \x in {0,1,2,3,4,5} {
                            \draw[thick,blue] (\x,0) -- (\x,5);
                        }
                        \foreach \y in {0,1,2,3,4,5} {
                            \draw[thick,blue] (0,\y) -- (5,\y);
                        }
                    \end{tikzpicture}
                </latex-image>
            </image>
        </sidebyside>
        <p>
            2. Each small square in the grid represents <m>0.1</m> unit in length.
        </p>
        <p>
            3. Count the total number of small squares in each grid.
        </p>
        <p>
            4. Determine the side length of each square grid by counting the number of small squares along one side.
        </p>
        <p>
            5. Analyze the relationship between the side length and the total number of squares in the grid. Write down your observations.
        </p>
        <p>
            6. Express both the side length and the total number of squares in fraction form. Observe the relationship between the numerators and denominators.
        </p>
    </activity>
    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                <ol cols="2" marker="a)">
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Work out: <m>\sqrt{0.81}</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Work out: <m>\sqrt{2.25}</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                <ol marker="a)">
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>\sqrt{0.81}</m>
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            <md>
                                <mrow> \text{Since } 0.81 can be written as the fraction \frac{81}{100}, we take the square root of both the numerator and the denominator separately. \amp </mrow>
                                <mrow>\sqrt{0.81} \amp = \sqrt{\frac{81}{100}} = \frac{\sqrt{81}}{\sqrt{100}}</mrow>
                                <mrow> \amp = \sqrt{\frac{2 \times 2 \times 2 \times 2 \times 3 \times 3 \times 3 \times 3}{2 \times 2 \times 5 \times 5}} </mrow>
                                <mrow> \amp = \frac{2 \times 2 \times 3 \times 3}{2 \times 5} = \frac{36}{10} </mrow>
                                <mrow> \amp= 3.6 </mrow>
                            </md>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>\sqrt{2.25}</m>
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            <md>
                                <mrow>\sqrt{2.25} \amp = \sqrt{\frac{225}{100}} </mrow>
                                <mrow> \amp = \sqrt{\frac{3 \times 3 \times 5 \times 5}{2 \times 2 \times 5 \times 5}} </mrow>
                                <mrow> \amp = \frac{5 \times 3}{2 \times 5} = \frac{15}{10} </mrow>
                                <mrow> \amp = 3.6 </mrow>
                            </md>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>
    

